english:
  title: Preface to the Collected Works of Minister Shin Mun-jung
  author: Kim Jong-jik
  language: eng
  text: |-
    How vastly different are the measures of human capacity! Cheng Yichuan once said: "Some possess the measure of a small vessel, some the measure of bronze cauldrons, some the measure of rivers, and some the measure of heaven and earth. The measure of a small vessel hardly deserves mention, yet even the bronze cauldron and river measures are considerable. Still, when filled, they overflow. Only the measure of heaven and earth can neither gain nor lose anything—and only the sage can truly embody it."

    Yet I believe the river, though it may sometimes overflow, cannot be ranked with the bronze cauldron's measure. However large a cauldron grows, it fills when many bushels are poured into it, but how could a river ever overflow from mere bushels? Therefore, only the great worthy and noble can embody the measure of rivers. Looking broadly across the ancients, few indeed achieved this. Among those I see today, is it not Minister Shin Mun-jung of Goryeong who comes closest?

    The Minister possessed a broad and expansive bearing, vast knowledge and learning. From the moment he entered service until he took his place in court, he applied what he had cultivated throughout his life to the work of governance. In all matters that arose, he met the moment with perfect response, attending left and right with such fluency that all marveled how each matter he handled revealed ever-deeper reserves of capacity, their depths unfathomable. Like the Yangtze and Yellow Rivers receiving all waters, even when struck by tempests and surging floods, they never spill over their banks.

    When he journeyed as envoy to Japan, he moved calmly through storm-tossed waves as though walking level ground. When he campaigned against northern barbarians, he rested serenely amid falling arrows as though sitting in his own hall. What matter the measure of those who would cast pregnant women into the sea or scheme to move camp in darkness? The difference speaks for itself.

    Nor was this excellence confined to his deeds. In his writings too, he grounded all in humanity and righteousness, loyalty and faith. His prose flows naturally and harmoniously, standing lofty and magnificent, requiring no harsh pruning yet possessing inherent form. The refined essence of the Former and Latter Han dynasties, the soaring elegance of the flourishing Tang—these shimmer forth in his every page. Even in playful turns of phrase or casual compositions, one perceives the words of one possessed of virtue. This too reflects his river-measure: vast, receiving all, flowing freely, meeting the wind to become myriad patterns, endless transformations—what mere brush and ink could capture?

    I, Jong-jik, am a late-coming provincial scholar who first came to know the Minister through the Hall of Succession. When he was composing his commentary on the military strategies, I was fortunate enough to serve under him. One day when I visited his residence, he was taking wine with guests. With a single word of praise to those assembled, he opened a path for my advancement. How could I ever forget such grace?

    Years after the Minister's passing, our sovereign lord, remembering his loyal servant, sought out his writings. The Minister's son, the Minister of Personnel, Jun, together with his cousin, the Vice-Director of the Court of Ceremonial Rites, compiled his works into several volumes and presented them. Our lord then commanded the National Academy of Letters to print and distribute them. Holding the volumes, I sighed and reflected: "The Minister's achievements and virtue cannot be fully contained in these pages, yet his spirit and bearing may be glimpsed here in some measure. During his lifetime, in governing the realm and discoursing on the Way, he illuminated the sovereign's transformative influence—who could recount it all? Yet now his legacy ascends to the throne above and spreads throughout the realm, so that the Minister shines in both life and memory. Though I, Jong-jik, could never offer even the smallest service in return for his recognition and kindness, I am honored now to append this preface. Let it simply testify to the Minister's expansive bearing and vast measure, that future scholars may have such materials for their records and praise."
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Cheng Yichuan (程伊川, 1033-1107) was a major Neo-Confucian philosopher of the Song dynasty, famous for his commentaries on the Classics and his theory of principle (li).
  - key: ''
    value: The reference to casting pregnant women into the sea alludes to a historical incident involving superstitious practice during storms, which Shin Suk-ju prevented—contrasting such petty fears with the Minister's expansive spirit.
  - key: ''
    value: Kim Jong-jik (1431-1492) was himself an important Neo-Confucian scholar and official of the Joseon dynasty; this preface is his tribute to an earlier generation of statesmen.
